 in the Family]]''\n| Policeman\n| Episode: \"A Moving Affair\" \n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 1984\n| ''West'' \n| Les \n| TV movie adaptation of [[Steven Berkoff]]'s play\n|-\n| ''[[The Bill]]''\n| Adam March\n| Episode:  \"Clutching at Straws\" \n|-\n| ''[[Diana (UK TV series)|Diana]]'' \n| Sergeant Grice\n| Episode 7\n|-\n| ''[[The Brief (TVS)|The Brief]]'' \n| Sergeant Davis RMP \n| Episode: \"People\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1985\n| ''Operation Julie'' \n| DC Malcolm Pollard \n| TV movie based on Dick Lee and Chris Pratt's nonfiction book ''[[Operation Julie]]: How the Undercover Police Team Smashed the World's Greatest Drugs Ring''\n|-\n| ''[[Oscar (TV serial)|Oscar]]'' \n| Warder Martin\n| Episode: \"De Profundis\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1987\n|''Lost Belongings'' \n| Simon Hunt \n| Episodes: \"The American Friend\" and \"Lenny Leaps In\"\n|-\n| ''The Bell-Run'' \n| Pace\n| TV movie\n|-\n| ''[[Miss Marple (TV series)|Miss Marple]]'' \n| Michael Rafiel \n| Episode: \"Nemesis\", an adaptation of [[Agatha Christie]]'s 1971 novel ''[[Nemesis (Christie novel)|Nemesis]]''\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[The Equalizer]]''\n| Greg Rivers\n| Episode: \"Eighteen with a Bullet\"\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''Storyboard''\n| Gerald \n| Episode: \"Snakes and Ladders\" \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1990\n| ''[[Yellowthread Street]]''\n| Nick Eden \n| Seven episodes, series based on the ''Yellowthread Street'' novels by [[William Leonard Marshall]]\n|-\n| ''[[Bergerac (TV series)|Bergerac]]''\n| Jake\n| Episode: \"The Messenger Boy\"\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Tales from the Crypt (TV series)|Tales from the Crypt]]''\n| Sergeant\n| Episode: \"Comes the Dawn\"\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[La Femme Nikita (TV series)|La Femme Nikita]]''\n| Jurgen\n| Episodes: \"Approaching Zero\", \"Third Person\", and \"Spec Ops\" \n|-\n| 1999\n|''[[Cleopatra (1999 film)|Cleopatra]]'' \n| [[Gaius Cassius Longinus|Cassius]] \n| TV movie adaptation of [[Margaret George]]'s 1997 [[historical fiction]] novel ''[[The Memoirs of Cleopatra]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2000\n| ''[[Britannic (film)|Britannic]]'' \n| Major Baker, MD \n| TV movie\n|-\n|''[[Apocalypse Revelation]]'' (aka ''San Giovanni \u2013 L'apocalisse'') \n| [[Domitian]]\n| TV movie\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2003\n| ''[[Dragnet (series)|Dragnet]]''\n| Alex Karp\n| Episode: \"All That Glitters\"\n|-\n| ''[[Keen Eddie]]''\n| Yellow\n| Episode: \"Horse Heir\"\n|-\n| ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]'' or ''MI-5''\n| Mickey Kaharias\n| Episode : \"Smoke and Mirrors\"\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Charmed]]''\n| Leader of the Order\n| Episode: \"[[Prince Charmed (Charmed Episode)|Prince Charmed]]\"\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Count Arthur Strong (TV series)|Count Arthur Strong]]''\n| Mr Duncan\n| Series 3 Episode: ''Arthur the Hat''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Theatre===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ As actor\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Julius Caesar (play)|Julius Caesar]]''\n| [[Julius Caesar]] \n| Directed by [[Michael Croft]] ([[Shaw Theatre]]); play by [[William Shakespeare]]\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''The Tale of Randy Robin''\n| Performer\n| Directed by [[John Godber]] (Cathedral Hall, [[Edinburgh]]); play by Michael Lawrence\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 1980\n|  ''[[The Pillars of Society]]'' \n| Karsten Bernick\n| Directed by [[Glyn Jones (South African writer)|Glyn Idris Jones]] (RADA); play by [[Henrik Ibsen]]\n|-\n| ''[[The Recruiting Officer]]''\n| Captain Plume\n| Directed by Euan Smith (RADA); play by [[George Farquhar]]\n|-\n| ''[['Tis Pity She's a Whore]]'' \n| Vasques\n| Directed by [[Adrian Noble]] (RADA); play by [[John Ford (dramatist)|John Ford]]\n|-\n| ''[[Macbeth]]'' \n|  [[Macbeth (character)|Macbeth]]\n|  Directed by Bruce Payne (RADA); play by William Shakespeare\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1981\n| ''No Names, No Medals''\n| SAS Soldier \n| Directed by Euan Smith (RADA); play by Euan Smith\n|-\n| ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]''\n| Cobweb \n| Directed by [[Richard Digby Day]] ([[Nottingham Playhouse]]); play by William Shakespeare\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1982\n| ''PIAF'' \n| [[Yves Montand]] \n| Directed by Jeremy Howe ([[York Theatre Royal]]); play by [[Pam Gems]]\n|-\n| ''[[Privates on Parade]]''\n| Flight sergeant Kevin Cartwright\n| Directed by [[Michael Blakemore]] ([[Derby Playhouse]]); play by [[Peter Nichols]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1983\n| ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]'' \n| [[Frank-N-Furter]]\n| Directed by Christopher Dunham ([[Palace Theatre, Westcliff-on-Sea]]); play by [[Richard O'Brien]]\n|-\n| ''West'' \n| Les\n| Directed by [[Steven Berkoff]] ([[Donmar Warehouse]]); play by Steven Berkoff\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''Alice'' \n| The Inventor\n| Directed by [[Nicholas Hytner]]  ([[Playhouse Theatre]]); a musical version of [[Lewis Carroll]]'s 1865 novel ''[[Alice in Wonderland]]''\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''Greek''\n| Eddy and Fortune-Teller\n| Directed by [[Steven Berkoff]] ([[Wyndhams Theatre]]); play by Steven Berkoff\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ As director\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''Macbeth''\n| Play by William Shakespeare\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''Greek'' \n| [[Mark Taper Forum]], [[Los Angeles]]; play by Steven Berkoff\n|-\n|}\n\n===Other Media===\n\nMusic Videos\n\n* [[Neil Young]]- ''Over and Over'' (1990) as a [[Stanley Kowalski]] esque character. Directed by [[Julien Temple]].\n\nTelevision Advertisements\n\n*[[Budweiser]] [[Bud Ice]] (1995) as a sinister spokesman.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0668271}}\n* Profile at International Artists Management: http://internationalartistsmanagement.co.uk/bruce-payne/\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Payne, Bruce}}\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:English male Shakespearean actors]]\n[[Category:English film producers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:National Youth Theatre members]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:1950s births]]\n[[Category:People from Addlestone]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Bruce Ryburn Payne}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Bruce Payne\n| image       =\n| caption     = \n| birthname   = Bruce Martyn Payne\n| birth_date  = {{Birth based on age as of date|47|2005|12|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Addlestone]], [[Woking]], [[Surrey]], England\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| othername   =\n| alma_mater  = [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n| occupation  = [[Actor]], [[film producer|producer]], [[screenwriter]], [[film director]], [[Theatre director]]\n| years active = 1981\u2013present\n| spouse      = \n| website     = \n}}\n'''Bruce Martyn Payne''' (born 1957 or 1958)<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4536150.stm |title=Flight arrest actor is cautioned |work=[[BBC]] |accessdate=29 August 2011 |date=16 December 2005}}</ref> is an English [[actor]], [[film producer|producer]], [[screenwriter]], [[film director]] and [[theatre director]]. Payne trained at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] (RADA) in [[London]] and was identified, in the late 1980s, with the \"[[Brit Pack (actors)|Brit Pack]]\" of rising young British actors. Payne is best known for portraying [[villain]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/games/iMEvil-Featuring-Halo-Wars-COD4-Voice-Talent-Is-Coming-Soon-18432.html# |first=William |last=Usher |title=iMEvil Featuring Halo Wars, COD4 Voice Talent Is Coming Soon |work=Cinemablend.com |date=1 July 2009 |accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvovermind.com/bruce-payne-deserves-way-credit-90s-bad-guy-persona/ |title=Bruce Payne Deserves Way More Credit for his 90s Bad Guy Persona |work=TVOverMind |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref> such as Charles Rane in ''[[Passenger 57]]'', Jacob Kell in ''[[Highlander: Endgame]]'', and Damodar in ''[[Dungeons & Dragons (film)|Dungeons & Dragons]]'' and ''[[Dungeons & Dragons: Wrath of the Dragon God|Dungeons & Dragons 2: Wrath of the Dragon God]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nPayne developed an interest for acting at an early age. In an interview with Impact magazine in 2001, Payne developed an interest for acting at an early age. In an interview with Impact magazine in 2001, Payne claimed that a crocodile from the play [[Peter Pan]] shouted that it would eat his brother and then proceeded to run up stage.<ref name=\"brucepayne.de\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brucepayne.de/press/articles/impact2001.html|title=Pleasure and Payne \u2013 Impact 2001|work=Brucepayne.de|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 14, he was diagnosed with a slight form of [[spina bifida]],<ref name=\"Cherreson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brucesangels.com/cosmomagazine.html|first=Adele|last=Cherreson|title=Payne Threshold|work=Cosmopolitan|accessdate=29 August 2011}}</ref> which by age 16 required surgery to rectify. Payne was hospitalised for 6 months following the operation.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nPayne continued school studies, despite a contact with a talent scout during that time. After his graduation, he enrolled in the [[National Youth Theatre]] for two seasons. Payne has described this experience as \"Four hundred kids thrown together to work on 7 plays.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agwlbp.com/damodartruth.html|first=Cory J.|last=Herndon|title=Truth or Damodar|work=[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]|date=1 January 2001|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> In addition, he was occupied with the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] for one season. He then auditioned for several fringe acting companies, but was told he was too young and lacked experience. However, in 1979, he was admitted to the \"prestigious\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=x47GQR6VcsEC&q=bruce+payne+royal+academy&dq=bruce+payne+royal+academy|first=Frank|last=Magill|title=Magill's Cinema Annual: 1993|work=Cengage Learning|year=1993|accessdate=4 November 2011|isbn=9780893564124}}</ref> RADA acting programme. Before being accepted at RADA, Payne worked as a joiner, a salesman, and a landscape gardener. Payne graduated from RADA in 1981 with seven major prizes for acting, comedy (Payne won the [[Fabia Drake]] Prize for Comedy) and physical presence.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nPayne was part of a 'new wave' of actors to emerge from the academy. Others included [[Jonathan Pryce]], [[Juliet Stevenson]], [[Alan Rickman]], [[Anton Lesser]], [[Kenneth Branagh]], and [[Fiona Shaw]]. In 1980 the Principal of RADA, [[Hugh Cruttwell]], selected a scene from an adaptation of [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Macbeth]]'', which Payne co-wrote with [[Paul McGann]], to be performed in front of [[Queen Elizabeth II]], in one of her rare visits to the academy. Payne directed the scene in which he and McGann acted. Payne played Macbeth and wielded a baseball bat on stage instead of a sword. [[Kenneth Branagh]] performed a soliloquy from ''[[Hamlet]]'' at the same event.<ref>The Royal Academy of Dramatic Art (1980) ''An Entertainment'', 19 November 1980 programme, GBS Theatre: London</ref>\n\n==Acting career==\n\n===1980s===\nPayne's first television role was in the ''Tales Out of School'' series. Payne played a PE teacher who 'comes across as more head bully than responsible adult during his classes'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://film.thedigitalfix.com/content/id/74335/tales-out-of-school.html|first=Anthony|last=Nield|title=Tales Out of School Blu Ray Review|work=The Digital Fix|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> His first major film role came in ''[[Privates on Parade (film)|Privates on Parade]]'' in which he played the singing and dancing [[Flight Sergeant]] Kevin Cartwright (whom he had already played in the stage version).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7hgQRVaWL-gC&pg=PA186|title=Ladies Or Gentlemen: A Pictorial ...|accessdate=8 May 2011|isbn=9781933231044|last1=Ginibre|first1=Jean-Louis|year=2005}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, he appeared in [[Michael Mann (director)|Michael Mann]]'s [[horror film]] ''[[The Keep (film)|The Keep]]'' as an unnamed border guard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flickeringmyth.com/2012/02/michael-mann-retrospective.html|first=Trevor|last=Hogg|title=A Michael Mann Retrospective|work=Flickering Myth|accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref> That same year, [[Steven Berkoff]] cast him in his production of ''West'' at the Donmar Warehouse. Payne played Les, a member of an [[East End of London|East End London]] gang intent on gaining revenge against the rival Hoxton Mob for the slaying of one of their number. [[Richard Corliss]] of ''TIME'' stated that Payne bestowed \"a frighteningly dynamic performance\" in the play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,926066,00.html|first=Richard|last=Corliss|title=Theater: Looking for the Real Thing|work=TIME|date=20 June 1983|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Payne was cast as a \"committed\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eyeforfilm.co.uk/reviews.php?film_id=11618|first=Sarah|last=Artt|title=Billy The Kid And The Green Baize Vampire|publisher=Eyeforfilm.co.uk |accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref> \"butch snooker manager\"<ref name=\"Hind\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brucesangels.com/theface.html|first=John|last=Hind|title=The Smart Money is on Bruce Payne|work=The Face|accessdate=29 August 2011}}</ref> known as \"The One\" (also known as \"T.O.\") in director [[Alan Clarke]]'s snooker musical ''[[Billy the Kid and the Green Baize Vampire]]''. Michael Brooke stated that Payne gave the \"stand-out performance\" in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/471094/index.html |first=Michael|last=Brooke|title=BFI Screenonline: Billy the Kid and the Green Baize Vampire (1985)|publisher=Screenonline.org.uk|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> and ''MS London'' stated that Payne 'is a charismatic presence, with a capable voice, who is perfectly cast as The One'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agwlbp.com/bruce1980.html|title=Bruce Payne \u2013 AGWLBP 1980's Bruce Bits |publisher=Agwlbp.com|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, both Payne and Berkoff appeared in [[Julien Temple]]'s musical ''[[Absolute Beginners (film)|Absolute Beginners]]'' . Payne played a psychotic<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NirkAAAAMAAJ&q=bruce+payne+berkoff&dq=bruce+payne+berkoff|title=The New Yorker, Volume 62, Issues 7\u201316|work=[[The New Yorker]]|year=1986|accessdate=4 May 2012}}</ref> \"pompous and pathetic racist\"<ref name=\"Hind\"/> named Flikker, who participated in the [[1958 Notting Hill race riots]]. One reviewer argued that Payne was \"the only actor to walk off ''Absolute Beginners'' with his reputation not only intact but enhanced\" and that his portrayal of Flikker \"was a headbutt of reality in a fantasmagoria of overkill.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brucepayne.de/press/articles/facearticle1987.html|first=Elissa|last=Van Poznack|title=The Brit Pack |work=The Face Magazine|date=1 January 1987|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> One critic stated that Payne gave a \"meaty, saving-grace performance\" in the film.<ref name=\"Hind\"/> The film journalist and editor, Ann Lloyd, selected Payne as the most promising newcomer of 1987 for his role in the film.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=An49AAAAMAAJ&dq=bruce+payne+actor&q=Best+Actor%3A+Bob+Hoskins#search_anchor|title=Films and Filming Issues 388\u201399|publisher=Hansom Books|accessdate=29 August 2011|year=1987}}</ref> In the same year Payne appeared in the film ''[[Solarbabies]]'', along with fellow British performer [[Alexei Sayle]], as filthy bounty hunters named Dogger and Malice. Payne said of his and Sayle's performances in ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' that \"the old image of an English arch-villain \u2013 [[Boris Karloff]], that sort of thing\" is turned \"upside down. We're just a couple of soaks\".<ref name=\"Irvine\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brucesangels.com/voguemagazine.html|first=Susan|last=Irvine|title=PAYNE speaking|work=[[Vogue In 1986 he played a part in the British television film The Bellrun, about 3 North Sea saturation deepsea divers He played a single devorced playboy diver part of a three man team, who gets involved with a female journalist that writes an article about North Sea offshore divers A good story, giving a good picture of the life divers lead offshore in their chambers and on their time off at home, entertaining lifestylemagazine)|Vogue]]|date=March 1987|accessdate=30 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Payne appeared as Eddy in the [[Steven Berkoff]]-directed play, ''Greek'' (a retelling of [[Sophocles]]' ''[[Oedipus Rex]]''), at the [[Wyndham's Theatre]]. Martin Hoyle, writing for ''[[The Independent]]'', stated that Payne's \"Eddy is vital, intelligent and physically disciplined in the best Berkoff style\".<ref name=\"agwlbp.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.agwlbp.com/greekjune2002.html |first=Martin |last=Hoyle |title=MONOMANIACAL LONDON |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> [[Charles Osborne (music writer)|Charles Osbourne]], writing for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', stated that Payne brought \"a cheerful zest to the role of Eddy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agwlbp.com/greekjune2002.html|first=Charles|last=Osborne|title=Full of sound and fury|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nA reviewer for ''[[The Listener (magazine)|The Listener]]'' stated that Payne \"impresses throughout\" the play.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WxlRAAAAYAAJ&q=bruce+payne+berkoff&dq=bruce+payne+berkoff|title=East End Oedipus|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=1 September 2011|year=1988}}</ref> Another reviewer stated that \"Payne gives a powerful performance as Eddy, the crusader out to defeat the horror of society\" only \"to find that he is part of the horror\".<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=rypaAAAAMAAJ&q=bruce+payne+horror&dq=bruce+payne+horror|title=London theatre record, Volume 8, Issues 1\u201313|publisher=London Theatre Record|year=1988|accessdate=5 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, he was cast in ''[[For Queen and Country]]'' as a 'drug kingpin'<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8QnsAAAAMAAJ&q=bruce+payne+acting&dq=bruce+payne+acting|title=For Queen and Country|work=The Film Journal|volume=92, Issues 1\u20136|publisher=Pubsun Corp|year=1989|accessdate=6 November 2011}}</ref> named Colin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/for-queen-and-country-1989|first=Roger|last=Ebert|title=FOR QUEEN AND COUNTRY|work=RogerEbert.com|year=1989|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nPayne and other young British actors who were becoming established film actors, such as [[Tim Roth]], [[Gary Oldman]], [[Colin Firth]], and [[Paul McGann]], were dubbed the '[[Brit Pack (actors)|Brit Pack]]'.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Payne's performances endeared him to [[Warner Bros.]], who considered \"Bruce Payne as [[Bruce Wayne]]\" on their \"one liner\" press marketing PR campaign for the first of [[Tim Burton]]'s ''[[Batman]]'' films. Ultimately, [[Michael Keaton]] got the role. Payne has commented, \"Warner were fascinated by the similarity\" between his name and that of Bruce Wayne. Payne has said that \"they drew up a very short shortlist and there I was on it. Obviously, I lost out in the end to Michael Keaton\".<ref name=\"http://www.agwlbp.com/sunday.html\">{{cite web|url=http://www.agwlbp.com/sunday.html|title=Bruce Payne Interview|publisher=Sunday Magazine|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the same year Payne appeared as Doctor Burton in the dramatic film ''[[Zwei Frauen]]'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&p_theme=sl&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB04CD44B2347BD&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |first=Joe|last=Pollack|title=Cliches Mar Woman's Tale Of Triumph Over Cancer ''SILENCE LIKE GLASS''|work=St. Louis Post Dispatch|date=31 August 1990|accessdate=31 October 2011}}</ref> The film was nominated for Outstanding Feature Film at the [[German Film Awards]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n===1990s===\n\nIn 1990 Payne appeared in the music video for [[Neil Young]]'s song ''Over and Over'', directed by [[Julien Temple]], as a [[Stanley Kowalski]] (played by [[Marlon Brando]] in ''[[A Streetcar Named Desire (1951 film)|A Streetcar Named Desire]]'', a film based on [[Tennessee Williams]]' play of the same name) esque character.\n\nIn 1991, Payne was cast as the Devil in ''[[Switch (1991 film)|Switch]]''. Payne was described as a \"delightfully wicked Satan\" by ''[[Film Review (magazine)|Film Review]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agwlbp.com/planepayne.html |first=Anwar |last=Brett |title=Plane Payne |work=Film Review |date = June 1993|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> ''[[The Providence Journal]]'' described him as a \"slick devil\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/projo/access/578853651.html?dids=578853651:578853651&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=May+10%2C+1991&author=MICHAEL+JANUSONIS+Journal-Bulletin+Arts+Writer&pub=The+Providence+Journal&desc=MOVIES+Comedy+that+hits+below+the+belt+Blake+Edwards+goes+for+bawdy+laughs+in+breezy+sex+farce&pqatl=google | first=Michael | last=Janusonis |title= Comedy that hits below the belt Blake Edwards goes for bawdy laughs in breezy sex farce |work=The Providence Journal |date=10 May 1991 |accessdate=21 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Payne was cast in his best-known role, opposite [[Wesley Snipes]], as a \"notorious terrorist and hijacker\",<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jHhbLBgVLS0C&pg=PA171&dq=bruce+payne+villain#v=onepage&q=bruce%20payne%20villain&f=false | first=Eric | last=Lichtenfeld |title=Action speaks louder: violence, spectacle, and the American action movie |publisher=Wesleyan University Press |year=2007 |accessdate=4 November 2011| isbn=9780819568014 }}</ref> with a steely, demonic nerve,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_G5KAAAAIBAJ&pg=1072,3370265&dq=bruce+payne+villain&hl=en | first=Steven | last=Rea | title=Action movie takes to skies with routine plot | work=[[The Vindicator]] | year=1992 |accessdate=8 September 2012}}</ref> named Charles Rane, in ''[[Passenger 57]]''. Marcus Trower of ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' stated that Payne was \"a brilliantly disconcerting madman. With his flowing blond Jesus locks, armour-piercing stare and casual sadism, he makes [[Hannibal Lecter]] look like a social worker \u2013 and like [[Anthony Hopkins]]' serial killer, part of the man's menace is in the apparent contradiction between his articulate, well-spoken English and his off-hand brutality.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=16898 |first=Marcus |last=Trower |title=Empire's Passenger 57 Movie Review |work=Empire  |date=5 December 2006 |accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> The ''[[Radio Times]]'' stated that Payne and Snipes both gave \"charismatic turns\" in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/film/9y4p/passenger-57-(1992) |first=John |last=Ferguson |title=Passenger 57 film review |work=Radio Times |accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' stated that Payne brought a 'tongue-in-cheek humor to the psychopathic fiend'.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9E0CE0DC1438F935A35752C1A964958260 | work=The New York Times | first=Stephen | last=Holden | title=Review/Film; Like a Roller Coaster, All Inside an Airplane | date=6 November 1992}}</ref> A reviewer for ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine stated that \"Bruce Payne steals the plane\u2014and the movie\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20109253,00.html |title=A Terrorist to Die for |work=People  |date=7 December 1992 |accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> In an article for the ''[[Waterloo Region Record]]'', Jamie Portman described Payne as a \"suave and cultivated English actor\" playing \"a suave and cultivated killer named Charles Rane\" and suggested that a \"key reason director Kevin Hooks chose him for the role was that he wanted a villain with as much magnetism as the hero\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/513775751.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+05%2C+1992&author=Jamie+Portman&pub=Waterloo+Region+Record&desc=Bruce+Payne+is+a+villain+with+charisma&pqatl=google | work=Waterloo Region Record | first=Jamie | last=Portman | title=Entertainment | date=5 November 1992}}</ref> Payne was described as \"icily perfect as the villainous Rane\" in the Worcester ''[[Telegram & Gazette]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=WO&p_theme=wo&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADEBE75B14FFD2&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | work=Telegram & Gazette | title=Passenger 57 is a New Twist on an Old Theme | date=6 November 1992}}</ref> Julius Marshall stated that Payne was \"ideal for his role: [[Superficial charm|charming]], dangerous \u2013 the kind of evil genius you love to hate\".<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=rlkbAQAAIAAJ&q=bruce+payne+evil&dq=bruce+payne+evil |first=Julius |last=Marshall |title=Action!: the action movie A-Z |publisher=Batsford |year=1996 |accessdate=1 September 2011|isbn=9780713478518 }}</ref> The ''[[Star Tribune]]'' stated that 'Bruce Payne makes a splendid psychopath, consistently stealing scenes from the likes of [[Wesley Snipes]] and [[Elizabeth Hurley]] throughout ''[[Passenger 57]]'''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MN&p_theme=mn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EFD5FC8546F66DF&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | work=[[Star Tribune]] | title=Critics' Choice | date=6 February 1998}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Payne played a \"charismatic\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://outnow.ch/Movies/1993/FullEclipse/Reviews/dvd/ |title=Full Eclipse (1993)|publisher=OutNow.ch |date=18 August 2003 |accessdate=31 October 2011}}</ref> werewolf named Adam Garou in ''[[Full Eclipse]]''. Joseph Savitski, who reviewed the film for Beyond Hollywood, stated, \"Payne is masterful as Detective Garou, a seductive and evil villain with arrogance and confidence to spare. When he's on screen, Payne demands the attention of the audience, and you're hard pressed to resist his performance. Payne is also the perfect adversary, the kind you're supposed to hate, but who has the charisma to draw you in nonetheless\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.beyondhollywood.com/full-eclipse-1993-movie-review/ |first=Joseph |last=Savitski |title=Full Eclipse (1993) Movie Review |publisher=BeyondHollywood.com |date=5 September 2004 |accessdate=8 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001191223/http://www.beyondhollywood.com/full-eclipse-1993-movie-review/ |archive-date=1 October 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Payne played a \"rogue FBI agent\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://movies.tvguide.com/one-mans-justice/review/131601 |title=One Man's Justice: Review |work=TV Guide |accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref> named Karl Savak in director [[Kurt Wimmer]]'s ''[[One Tough Bastard]]''. One reviewer described Savak as one of the most 'entertaining movie villains in low budget action flick history' and noted that 'so awesome is Karl Savak that some lunatic has created a [[Facebook]] page in his honor'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmcriticsunited.com/onemansjustice.html |first=Christopher |last=Armstead |title=One Man's Justice |work=Film Critics United |accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref> Another reviewer stated that 'Bruce Payne, with his [[Whitesnake]] hair and nose ring is slimeball perfection as the villain'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thevideovacuum.livejournal.com/1275026.html |first=Mitch |last=Lovell |title=Legends of the Silver Screen: Brian Bosworth |work=The Video Vacuum |date=22 December 2012 |accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref>\nIn 1998, he played Jurgen, a first-class and charismatic operative in season two of ''[[La Femme Nikita]]''.\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2000, Payne portrayed the villain Jacob Kell in ''[[Highlander: Endgame]]'' (2000), the third sequel to the original ''[[Highlander (film)|Highlander]]'' film.  One reviewer said of ''Highlander: Endgame'', \"the one in the cast that seems to be having the most fun is Bruce Payne. Traditionally, ''Highlander'' villains give performances that go completely over-the-top and well into the stratosphere. Payne contrarily gives a performance where he enunciates every syllable with relish and dramatic weight, resulting in a performance that is entirely captivating whenever he is on screen.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moria.co.nz/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1820Itemid=1|first=Richard|last=Scheib|title=HIGHLANDER: ENDGAME|work=moria.co.nz|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Salon.com]]'s reviewer wrote that \"[Payne] playing Kell as a cockney thug with triple crucifixes embedded in the heels of his Doc Martens, Payne is more fun than either of the stars\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/entertainment/movies/review/2000/09/01/highlander_endgame|title=Highlander: Endgame|work=Salon |date=1 September 2000|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> A reviewer for ''Trash City'' stated that \"''Endgame'' is pretty good, largely thanks to Bruce Payne's efforts as the bad guy, who is right up there with [[Clancy Brown]]'s original decapitator\", the [[Kurgan (Highlander)|Kurgan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trashcity.org/BLITZ/BLIT0919.HTM|title=Trash City review: Highlander \u2013 Endgame|work=Trashcity.org|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> Marke Andrews, writing for ''[[The Vancouver Sun]]'', stated that Payne provided the \"focal point\" in the film and that he dived \"into his role with gusto\". Andrews also stated that Payne's 'facial expressions rival [[Jim Carrey]]'s in ''[[The Mask (1994 film)|The Mask]]'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agwlbp.com/highlander2.html|first=Marke|last=Andrews|title=Highlander: Endgame Vancouver Province Review|work=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> Cherriece Wright, who reviewed the film for ''[[The Dispatch (Lexington)|The Dispatch]]'', stated that it contained \"brilliant performances by [[Christopher Lambert]] and Bruce Payne\". Wright stated that Payne \"delivers a great performance as Jacob Kell blending smoothly the malicious vindictiveness of the embittered immortal with a sarcastic wit that provides needed humor\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uK0cAAAAIBAJ&pg=3164,404846&dq=bruce+payne+film&hl=en |first=Cherriece|last=Wright|title=Highlander: Endgame offers an OK outing|work=The Dispatch|date=7 September 2000|accessdate=20 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the same year, Payne played Damodar in ''[[Dungeons & Dragons (film)|Dungeons & Dragons]]'', henchman of the malevolent Profion (played by [[Jeremy Irons]]). Although the film was critically panned, Payne's performance was reviewed favourably. One reviewer said that \"Bruce Payne (Damodar) as Profion's nefarious assistant in his power-hungry schemes was the stand-out performance of all the actors in the film. Payne has a true lock on how to play a character that is menacing even without any show of power. His portrayal of Damodar calls to mind [[Doug Bradley]]'s portrayal of [[Pinhead (Hellraiser)|Pinhead]] in the ''Hellraiser'' films, so coldly, coolly arrogant and confident is his character. Above and beyond the grade I give to this film, Payne has earned himself an A+ in my gradebook.\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20041229210202/http://csc.aix.cc/profj/dnd.htm Dungeons and Dragons]. Prof J's Movie Reviews</ref> Another reviewer stated that Payne's performance proved that he is \"one of Hollywood's more reliable villains\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tnmc.org/batcave/dandd.html|first=John|last=Shea|title=TNMC Movies: Reviews: Dungeons & Dragons|work=Tnmc.org|accessdate=8 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718144327/http://www.tnmc.org/batcave/dandd.html|archivedate=18 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nBranden Chowen, who reviewed the film for ''Indie Pulse'', stated that \"the standout in the film is the man who returns for the sequel: Bruce Payne. His character is written to be one-note throughout, but Payne still manages to create an excellent villain. Once the audience gets past his blue lipstick, which is no small feat, Payne is a formidable and passionate force\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidepulse.com/2011/03/30/dungeons-dragons-2-movie-collection-blu-ray-review|first=Branden|last=Chowen|title=Dungeons & Dragons 2-Movie Collection \u2013 Blu-ray Review|work=Inside Pulse|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> ''[[The Charlotte Observer]]'' stated that \"menacing Bruce Payne gives the film's one potent performance\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CO&s_site=charlotte&p_multi=CO&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F2442C7EB660740&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=DUNGEONS' BAFFLES WITH ITS MANY-FACETED POINTLESSNESS|work=The Charlotte Observer|date=8 December 2000}}</ref> Abbie Bernstein for ''Audio Video Revolution'' declared that Payne was \"enjoyably evil as the secondary baddie in charge of capturing the rebels\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avrev.com/dvd-movie-disc-reviews/sci-fi-fantasy/dungeons-dragons.html|first=Abbie|last=Bernstein|title=Dungeons & Dragons|work=Audio Video Revolution|date=22 May 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Payne appeared as the \"snarling\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117922867?refcatid=31|work=Variety|first=Scott|last=Foundas|title=One Point O|date=19 January 2004}}</ref> Neighbour, who \"dabbles\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.horschamp.qc.ca/new_offscreen/onepoint.html|first=Donato|last=Totaro|title=One Point 0 Interview|work=Offscreen|date=31 July 2004|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> in producing kinky virtual games<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/ff20050629a2.html|first=Giovanni|last=Fazio|title=It's all in your coding|work=Japan Times|date=29 June 2005|accessdate=21 April 2012}}</ref> in the dystopian horror mystery<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=33157|first=Owen|last=Williams|title=Laurence Fishburne Heads To The Colony|work=Empire|date=2 March 2012|accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref> ''[[Paranoia 1.0]]''. The film was nominated in the best film category at the [[Sitges - Catalan International Film Festival]] and at the [[Sundance Film Festival]], and won the best film award at the Malaga International Week of Fantastic Cinema. John Fallon stated that as the Neighbour, Payne \"laid on the charisma and the macho-ness thick\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Sampson|first=Mike|url=https://www.joblo.com/arrow/onepointo.htm|title=One Point O (2004)|work=JoBlo.com|date=13 May 2002|accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Payne returned to the role of Damodar in ''[[Dungeons & Dragons: Wrath of the Dragon God]]''. Payne was the only member of the original cast in the sequel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/20013/dungeons-and-dragons-2-wrath-of-the-dragon-god|title=Dungeons and Dragons 2 \u2013 Wrath of the Dragon God|work=DVDTalk|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he helped to launch the [[National Youth Theatre]]'s 50th-anniversary programme along with [[Ian McKellen|Sir Ian McKellen]], [[Timothy Spall]], [[Diana Quick]], [[Paula Wilcox]], Jonathan Wrather, newsreader [[Krishnan Guru-Murthy]], and ''[[Little Britain]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Matt Lucas (comedian)|Matt Lucas]] and [[David Walliams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/photos/theatre/london/E8821143644917/Photos:+NYT+Celebrates+50+Years+of+Star+Support.html|title=Photos: NYT Celebrates 50 Years of Star Support \u2013 \u2013 Photos|work=Whatsonstage.com|date=11 October 2005|accessdate=8 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615175323/http://www.whatsonstage.com/photos/theatre/london/E8821143644917/Photos:+NYT+Celebrates+50+Years+of+Star+Support.html|archive-date=15 June 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===2010s===\n\nIn 2011, Payne appeared in the horror film ''[[Prowl (film)|Prowl]]'' as a \"blatantly untrustworthy\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fearnet.com/news/reviews/b21608_after_dark_originals_prowl_movie_review.html |first=Scott |last=Weinberg |title=After Dark Originals 'Prowl' Movie Review |work=FEARnet |date=1 February 2011 |accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref> \"hillbilly truck driver\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/Jason_Coleman/2011/04/12/dvd_review_after_dark_husk_prowl |first=Jason |last=Coleman |title=DVD Review: After Dark 'Husk' & 'Prowl' |work=Starpulse.com |date=12 April 2011 |accessdate=31 October 2011}}</ref> named Bernard in the film. Matt Withers, who reviewed the film for [[JoBlo.com]], stated that \"Bruce Payne shows up as a trucker in a throwaway role that he makes anything but\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joblo.com/arrow/dvd_reviews.php?id=2770 |first=Matt |last=Withers |title=The DVD Pub reviews Prowl |work=Joblo.com |accessdate=8 May 2011}}</ref>  Payne also appeared in ''[[Carmen's Kiss]]'' (an adaptation of the [[Georges Bizet]] opera ''[[Carmen]]'').\n\nIn 2012, Payne voiced a [[demon]] in the [[found footage (pseudo-documentary)|found-footage]] horror film ''[[Greystone Park (film)|Greystone Park]]'' (also known as ''The Asylum Tapes'').\n\nIn 2013, Payne appeared in the Warner Bros. action film ''[[Getaway (film)|Getaway]]''.{{cn|date=April 2020}} Payne also appeared in the action film ''[[Vendetta (2013 film)|Vendetta]]'' as a sinister [[Whitehall]] [[Mandarin (bureaucrat)|Mandarin]] named Mr. Rooker.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=VendettaFilm|author=VENDETTA|number=336439878415970306|date=20 May 2013|title=Hollywood bad guy BRUCE PAYNE is sinister Whitehall mandarin MR ROOKER in vigilante movie @VendettaFilm RT}}</ref> One reviewer of the film gave it eight out of ten and stated that Payne 'nearly steals the movie with a plum role as the icy head of British black ops'.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://britpic.wordpress.com/ |title=Vendetta |work=Britpic |date=20 November 2012 |accessdate=20 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130416110148/http://britpic.wordpress.com/ |archive-date=16 April 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  In addition, Payne portrayed Auschwitz camp Commandant Rudolf Hoess, in a 'superciliously evil' manner,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2014/more/reviews/film-review-victor-young-perez-1201111386/ |first=Dennis |last=Harvey |title=Film Review: 'Victor ''Young'' Perez' |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=19 February 2014 |accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> in the French film ''[[Victor Young Perez (film)|Victor Young Perez]]'', which concerns the life of the [[Tunisia]]n [[Jew]] [[flyweight]] [[boxer]] [[Victor Perez]].\n\nIn 2015, Payne played Winston, a religious fanatic,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3366083/review-re-kill-another-unfortunate-case-done/|title=[Review] 'Re-Kill' is Another Unfortunate Case of 'Been There, Done That'|last=Torfe|first=Pat|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|date=2015-10-19|accessdate=2016-04-24}}</ref> in the horror film ''[[Re-Kill]]''.\n\nIn 2018 Payne appeared in the [[Anthology film]] ''[[London Unplugged]]'', which premiered at the [[East End Film Festival]].\n\n===2020s===\n\nPayne played the main antagonist in ''[[Creators: The Past]]'' (which he also produced and acted as assistant director for), which is due to be released in 2020. Payne has also been cast as [[Frank Warren (promoter)|Frank Warren]] in ''Michael-The Michael Watson Story'', a biopic of boxer [[Michael Watson]].\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ As actor\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Director\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Privates on Parade (film)|Privates on Parade]]''  \n| Flight Sergeant Kevin Cartwright\n| [[Michael Blakemore]]\n| Based on the [[Peter Nichols]] play ''[[Privates on Parade]]''\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[The Keep (film)|The Keep]]'' \n| Border Guard #2\n| [[Michael Mann (director)|Michael Mann]]\n| Based on [[F. Paul Wilson]]'s 1981 novel ''[[The Keep (Wilson novel)|The Keep]]''\n|-\n| 1984 \n| ''[[Oxford Blues]]'' \n| Peter Howles\n| [[Robert Boris]]\n| A remake of the 1938 film ''[[A Yank at Oxford]]''\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Billy the Kid and the Green Baize Vampire]]''\n| T.O. (The One)\n| [[Alan Clarke]]\n| Loosely based on the rivalry between the [[snooker]] players [[Ray Reardon]] and [[Jimmy White]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2019/04/lets-get-weird-cinematic-oddities/|first=Tom|last=Jolliffe|title=Let's Get Weird! Cinematic Oddities|work=Flickering Myth|accessdate=13 April 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 1986\n| ''[[Absolute Beginners (film)|Absolute Beginners]]'' \n| Flikker\n| [[Julien Temple]]\n| Based on [[Colin MacInnes]] 1959 novel ''[[Absolute Beginners (novel)|Absolute Beginners]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Smart Money (1986 film)|Smart Money]]'' \n| Lawrance MacNiece\n| [[Bernard Rose (director)|Bernard Rose]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Solarbabies]]'' \n| Dogger\n| [[Alan Johnson (choreographer)|Alan Johnson]]\n|\n|-\n| ''Caprice''\n| Jack\n| [[Joanna Hogg]]\n| Short Film\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[The Fruit Machine (1988 film)|The Fruit Machine]]'' or ''Wonderland'' \n| Echo\n| [[Philip Saville]]\n|Speaks not a wo